        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2013-03-18 15:07:18.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3:\n\nBob,\n\nI made the code changes, committed locally, then when I tried to push, Gerrit rejected the patch saying there were no changes.  I tried a few times with no luck.\n\nA quick look online suggested applying a new change ID, but that of course creates an entire new change.  I made another trivial change, and this time, Gerrit let me push.\n\nDo you have a recommendation for dealing with this gracefully?  I'd rather not create a new change, but that's the only way I know of to get the code changes to appear correctly.\n- Patrick",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "2e15e96c046e4afc08ff2c31475742cbd32049b4",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 251,
        "name": "Bob Glossman",
        "email": "bob.glossman@intel.com",
        "username": "bogl",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2013-03-18 15:15:23.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3:\n\nPatrick,\n  I am not sure what is wrong.  The fact that the gerrit thinks this change is dependent on an (ABANDONED) change suggests that you are working in a branch with other not to be committed things in it.  I would start over in a fresh branch cloned from current master,  commit this change fresh using identical commit header and change ID, then try pushing that.\n\nBob",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
